				<li id="16784796" class="cmnt-root" data="0" data-d="1665374039000"><ul class="comments"><li class="comment-box"><div class="avatar"><img src="/images/avatar.png" alt="" /><div class="comment-username">Anonymous</div></div><div class="comment"><div class="title"><span class="txt-subject"></span><input style="display: none;" class="txt-subject-ed"><span class="right cmt-ui"><a href="https://fextralife.com/forums/t579028/Ruins-Greatsword" rel="nofollow" target="_blank">09 Oct 2022 23:53</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;<a class="report-post" href="https://fextralife.com/forums/report.php?f=193&p=16784796" rel="nofollow" target="_blank" title="report this post"><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-flag" aria-hidden="true"></span></a></span></div><p class="txt-comment">This sword does a bit more damage with most attacks than a heavy greatsword at high strength levels (all light attacks and jumping, rolling, back-step heavy attacks) thanks to its extremely high strength scaling and added magic damage. However, its basic R2 attacks seem to have low attack modifiers and do less damage uncharged. When the heavy attacks are charged, they will out-damage the greatsword&apos;s charged R2s only if the gravity burst hits, otherwise the sword alone does less. Though the gravity effect will hit most of the time when the sword does, the range is extremely short, so if the sword knocks the target back even a little it may miss. Just something to be mindful of.</p><textarea style="display: none;" class="txt-comment-ed"></textarea><div class="clearfix"><a role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#zz-16784796" class="cmt-reply pull-right" href=""><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-share-alt"></span>Reply</a><a id="btnExpandComment" role="button" data-toggle="collapse" href="#replies-16784796" class="cmt-reply pull-right" href=""><span class="glyphicon glyphicon-share-alt"></span>Replies (<span class="replies">0</span>)</a><div class="vote pull-right"><section class="t-up"><span></span><p>0</p><i class="